default7.
default              
defaultI would not for a moment argue that the human race has had no impact at all on the climate. But, in my submission, the whole idea of 
defaultMMGW
default has been grotesquely exaggerated, by too many
default people
default, 
defaulton the basis of highly questionable evidence, 
defaultover the last quarter century. The world has been warming &amp; cooling ever since it began, around 4.5
default&#xa0;
defaultBn BC. As the "Economist" has recently reminded us 
default- 
defaultsee article on “The Cambrian Explosion” on p 87 of the 23 March Issue
default -
default during "The Snowball Earth" Era, which lasted from around 725 Mn. BC to around 541 Mn BC, there were a series of Ice Ages, which were, at their maxima, among the most extensive glaciations in the world's history. They alternated, though, with periods when the planet's average temperature was sometimes as high as 50 Degrees C. None of this was due to MM
defaultGW
default. Man was simply not around in those days. The first Homo Erectus, predecessor of Human Beings (Homo Sapiens), emerged around BC 2 Mn. Homo Sapiens came into existence in 
defaultAfrica
default ca. 200,000 BC, and rapidly spread round the world. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default8.
default              
defaultBetween 1975 and 1998, there was clearly a rise in world 
defaultaverage 
defaulttemperatures. In the latter year, therefore, it could have seemed reasonably logical to suggest that this was due to the rapidly increasing global emissions of CO2
default, which averaged 1.5 ppm per annum over that period (NOAA data).
default. In 1998, however, the increase of world temperatures halted. Since then, for 15 years, 
defaultglobal
default 
defaultaverage 
defaulttemperatures have been virtually static. During the same period, global CO2 emissions rose 
defaulteven faster, at 1.85 ppm per annum, or almost 8%. 
defaultThe argument that CO2 emissions contribute to an important extent to climate change has therefore been 
defaultsteadily 
defaultweaken
defaulting, year by year, for 15 years, and is no longer valid
default&#xa0;
default9.
default              
defaultMost 
defaultreasonably 
defaultwell 
defaultinformed 
defaultpeople are aware of the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change of 9 May 1992. Its ultimate aim was declared to be the stabilisation of greenhouse gas [GHG] concentrations in the atmosphere at a level which would prevent dangerous anthropogenic interference with the climate system. It was followed by the Kyoto Protocol (to the Convention) of 11 Dec 1997. This set targets, though for Developed Countries only: amongst the latter, moreover, there were notable exceptions from the ratification process, including the 
defaultUSA
default &amp; 
defaultAustralia
default. The key aim was that Contracting States should – over the period 2008 to 2012 – each reduce their GHG emissions by 5% compared with 1990.
default&#xa0;
default10.
default              
defaultIn December 2007, there took place in 
defaultBali
default a Conference of the Parties to the Kyoto Protocol, along with certain other countries, making a total of over 180 States. This Conference took into account the work of the 
defaultInternational Panel for Climate Change (
defaultIPCC
default)
default. It agreed two key documents. The first was the Bali Road Map. This envisaged the preparation of a new Agreement on Climate Change, intended for adoption at a similar conference in 
defaultCopenhagen
default in December 2009. The
default&#xa0;
defaultpreparatory work was entrusted to an Ad Hoc Working Group on Long
default&#x2011;
defaultTerm Cooperative Action [AHWG-LTCA]. The Working Group was asked to provide a progress report in time for consideration at a similar conference in 
defaultPoznan
default, 
defaultPoland
default, in December 2008. The second was the Bali Action Plan. This document is essentially a list of rather general ideas to be studied by the 
defaultAHWG-LTCA.
