default14.
default              
defaultIn June 2011, the Global Warming Policy Foundation published a Report on climate change by Lord Turnbull. Few people could speak 
defaulton this subject 
defaultwith more authority: Lord Turnbull was, successively, Head of the Department of the Environment (1994-98), then Head of the Treasury (1998-2002), and finally Cabinet Secretary &amp; Head of the Civil Service (2002-2005).  In 
defaulthis Report
default he stated the following
default. 
defaultThere is huge controversy about the relative contribution of man-made CO2 versus natural forces such as the sun, cosmic rays, clouds and the oceans. Many scientists would support an alternative hypothesis that the globe has been on a gentle warming trend since the end of the Little Ice Age around two hundred years ago, with alternating periods measured in decades of faster and slower growth, or even periods of moderate decline. Such an alternative view would not justify the alarmism which characterizes much of the public debate.
default 
defaultThe Really Inconvenient Truth is that the propositions of the IPCC do not bear the weight of certainty with which they are expressed. However, 
defaulthe wrote, 
defaultthe purpose of 
defaulthis
default paper 
defaultwa
defaults not to argue that there is another truth which should become the new consensus, but to point out the doubts that exist about the IPCC viewpoint
default,
default and 
defaultthe 
defaultserious flaws in its procedures. It 
defaultwa
defaults also to question why the UK Government has placed such heavy bets on one particular source of advice. The economic policy choices being made w
defaultould
default not minimize the cost of
default mitigation. The paper concluded
default with a call for more humility from scientists, more rational reflection from politicians, and more challenge from our parliamentarians.
