default              
defaultThe problem of GHG emissions of human origin must, in any case, be kept in correct perspective. The world
default's climate
default is always at risk from other causes - for example a meteor strike. GHG can emerge in nature – e.g.
default&#xa0;
defaultthrough massive volcanic explosions, as at Krakatoa. And they are by no means the only influence on our climate. Sunspots constitute another major one. For 12,000 years we have been in the run-down from the last ice
default&#x2011;
defaultage. Glaciers have been receding. But there have been speed
default&#x2011;
defaultups and slow
default&#x2011;
defaultdowns in the process - often very large. There were mini
default&#x2011;
defaultIce
default&#x2011;
defaultAges in the Dark Ages (540
default&#x2011;
default950); and again between 1300 and 1850. These produced intense cold, untimely frosts and widespread famine. The production of GHG 
defaultin that period
default was insignificant by comparison with today.
default It should also be borne in mind that fossil-fuel burning is not the only source of CO2 em
defaultissions. Currently 7,333 MT of CO2
default are released annually,
default as forests are destroyed. (The latter process
default is politely called ‘change of land use’).
default American researchers have 
defaultalso 
defaultdiscovered that the amount of water high in the atmosphere is far more influential on world temperatures than previously thought. A study, published in the journal Science [January 2010], says that a 10 % drop in humidity 10
default&#xa0;
defaultmiles above the Earth's surface explains why global temperatures have been stable since the start of the
default 21st 
defaultcentury, despite the rise in carbon dioxide in the atmosphere. A rise in water vapour in the 1980’s and 90’s may also explain why temperatures shot up so quickly in the previous two decades, they say.
